Part 3: Working with Categorical Variable

In this part of the project, we will create lists to specify the order for each of the three categorical variables.

In[9]:
clarity_levels = ['I1', 'SI2', 'SI1', 'VS2', 'VS1', 'VVS2', 'VVS1', 'IF'] 
cut_levels = ['Fair', 'Good', 'Very Good', 'Premium', 'Ideal']
color_levels = ['J', 'I', 'H', 'G', 'F', 'E', 'D' ]

We will now use these lists to communicate to Pandas the correct order for the levels of the three categorical variables.

In[10]:
diamonds.loc[:, 'cut'] = pd.Categorical(diamonds['cut'], categories=cut_levels)
diamonds.loc[:, 'color'] = pd.Categorical(diamonds['color'], categories=color_levels)
diamonds.loc[:, 'clarity'] = pd.Categorical(diamonds['clarity'], categories=clarity_levels)

We will now create lists of named colors to serve as palettes to be used for visualizations later in the notebook.

In[11]:
clarity_pal = ['brown', 'orange', 'deeppink', 'cyan', 'red', 'blue', 'yellow', 'lime']
cut_pal = ['cyan', 'darkcyan', 'forestgreen', 'lime', 'gold']
color_pal = ['slateblue', 'darkorchid','mediumvioletred', 'crimson','green', 'darkorange', 'gold']

Part 5: Scatterplots of Price Against Carat

In this part of the project, we will start by plotting all the diamond data in one scatterplot. Then well color the points by clarity level and finally split them into separate subplots so each clarity gets its own visual for easy comparison.

In[15]:
y = diamonds.loc[:, 'price']
x = diamonds.loc[:, 'carat']

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 6])

plt.scatter(x, y, s=20 , c='purple', alpha=0.4)  

plt.xlabel("Carat Size")  # X-axis label
plt.ylabel("Price (in $)")  # Y-axis label
plt.title("Relationship between Diamond Price and Carat Size")  

plt.show()

Now we will reproduce the plot from above, but will now color the points according to their clarity.

In[16]:
plt.figure(figsize=[8, 6])

for i in range(len(clarity_levels)):
    clarity = clarity_levels[i]
    color = clarity_pal[i]
    
    x = diamonds.loc[diamonds.loc[:, 'clarity'] == clarity, 'carat']
    y = diamonds.loc[diamonds.loc[:, 'clarity'] == clarity, 'price']
    
    plt.scatter(x, y, s=20 , c=color, alpha=0.4, label=clarity) 

plt.xlabel("Carat Size")
plt.ylabel("Price (in $)")
plt.title("Relationship between Diamond Price and Carat Size")

plt.legend(title="Clarity")
Out[16]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x1a3311f99d0>

We will now separate the points for each of the eight clarity levels into its own subplot.

In[17]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

for i in range(8):
    plt.subplot(2, 4, i + 1)  
    clarity = clarity_levels[i]
    color = clarity_pal[i]

    x = diamonds.loc[diamonds.loc[:, 'clarity'] == clarity, 'carat']
    y = diamonds.loc[diamonds.loc[:, 'clarity'] == clarity, 'price']
    
    plt.scatter(
        x,
        y,
        s=20,
        color=color,      
        alpha=0.4,       
    )
    plt.xlim([0, 4])
    plt.ylim([0, 20000])
    plt.title(clarity)
    plt.xlabel("Carat Size")
    plt.ylabel("Price (in $)")


plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Part 6: Applying Logarithmic Transformations

We will start by adding two new columns to the diamonds in order to store the transformed variables.

In[18]:
diamonds.loc[:, 'ln_carat'] = np.log(diamonds.loc[:, 'carat'])
diamonds.loc[:, 'ln_price'] = np.log(diamonds.loc[:, 'price'])

We will now use histograms to explore the distribution of the diamond prices, and the log of the diamond prices.

In[19]:
plt.figure(figsize=[12, 4])  

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.hist(
    x=diamonds.loc[:, 'price'] , 
    bins=20,          
    color='green',         
    edgecolor='k',     
)

plt.xlabel("Price")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.title("Histogram of Prices")

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)

plt.hist(
    x=diamonds.loc[:, 'ln_price'],            
    bins=20,          
    color='darkviolet',         
    edgecolor='k',     
)

plt.xlabel("Natural Log of Price")
plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.title("Histogram of Log-Prices")

plt.show()

We will now use histograms to explore the distribution of the carat sizes, and the log of the carat sizes.

In[20]:
plt.figure(figsize=[12, 4])  

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.hist(
    x=diamonds.loc[:, 'carat'] ,

    color='darkorange',         
    edgecolor='k',     
)

plt.ylabel("Count")
plt.title("Histogram of Carat Sizes")

    x=diamonds.loc[:, 'ln_carat'],

    edgecolor='k',     
)
